post_text: We have been working with the county health department and the state epidemiologist from the Oklahoma State Department of Health to make recommendations of quarantine after we were notified of a COVID-19 positive case involving the high school football team. After investigating and consulting with the epidemiologist, it was determined that the team and associated personnel will be quarantined for 14 days, with an ending date of September 19, 2020. We continue to work with the health department on mitigation strategies to keep our students and the community safe.

This week‚Äôs Tuesday Teacher Feature is John Moreno. This is John‚Äôs fourth year with Ardmore City Schools; 3.5 as a teacher and .5 as a student teacher. During his time with Ardmore Bands, he has directed the Pride of Ardmore Marching Band, AHS Symphonic Band, AMS Beginning Band, AMS Intermediate Band, and AMS Advanced Band. He also writes marching drill and arranges music for The Pride of Ardmore. John is a charismatic leader that is well liked by his students. He has made a tremendous impact on the middle school program and provided our band programs with a much needed boost. All three middle school bands have developed continuity and skills improvement as well as nearly doubling in size.

During the virus shutdown, he was known to spice up his online presence by teaching class in a dinosaur outfit. Now that is thinking outside the box.

We are thrilled to have John as a part of the ACS Family.

post_text: Have you ever wondered how the school district is able to keep Noble Stadium in tip top shape? Well, there‚Äôs two people that make it happen year around, Chris Ezeobele and J.D. Douglas. On ‚Äúgame weeks‚Äù these two guys start their week off by picking up trash, trimming hedges, mowing, weed eating, cleaning the press box, cleaning home and visitor restrooms, cleaning the parking lots, pressure washing the breezeways, sweeping the turf, hanging the flags, setting out cones and the list goes on. Without the dedication and hard work these two put in week after week the stadium might look a little different. So, anytime you attend an event at Noble Stadium, take pride in the work that is put into keeping it so nice and when you‚Äôre there, find these two guys and tell them thank you!

It's Tuesday Teacher Feature time. Behind that mask is our new music teacher at the Will Rogers Early Childhood Center, Mrs. Paige Anderson. When you enter her room you will immediately notice a whole lot of activity, smiling faces and beautiful little voices. Students can‚Äôt wait for Mrs. Anderson‚Äôs classes. She makes learning fun.

This is the first time we have had a fine arts program at the Will Rogers Early Childhood Center. We know from research that students who engage in the arts consistently fare better in their math and reading classes than those who do not. And the social and emotional benefits to children who experience an artistic outlet are priceless.

A big Ardmore Tiger welcome to Mrs. Paige Anderson! We are thrilled to have you rejoin the ACS Family.

The Lady Tigers Softball program is looking BRIGHT! Tiger fans help us welcome new head coach, Darrell Mays!

Coach Mays is starting his first year as the head varsity softball coach and his 11th year at ACS. Prior to returning to ACS, he was the head varsity softball & baseball coach at Dickson High School. In 2017 Coach Mays won the Daily Ardmoreite Baseball Coach of the Year. Coach Mays has been coaching for 20 years. His coaching assignments consist of head varsity football, girls basketball & softball at Thackerville High School; Head Varsity boys baseball and basketball at LeFlore High School; varsity football & Baseball at Tishomingo. Coach Mays attended SOSU receiving his degree in Exercise Science in 1998 and his M.Ed from ECU in 2002.

A Message from ACS Director of Indian Education, Kim Smith.

To Indian Education Johnson O'Malley (JOM) Students/Parents
Due to the Covid19 shutdowns causing delays in the JOM grant approvals, the Chickasaw Nation anticipates that JOM school supplies will not be able to disburse until October of this year.

Your JOM department offers their sincere apologies for this delay. We will be glad to assist with school supplies as soon as we are approved to do so.

For more information contact Kim Smith, ksmith@ardmoreschools.org or 580-226-7652

Help us welcome our new Ardmore High School Girls and Boys Soccer Coach, John Connor!

A native of Mallorca, Spain, John Connor earned a bachelor‚Äôs degree in psychology at East Central in May 2019 from ECU and is currently pursuing a master‚Äôs degree in sports administration.

Coach Connor moved to the USA in 2014 to pursue his dream of playing college soccer, where he played for Murray State College and USAO. Connor stoped playing college Soccer in his Senior year due to injury and decided to focus on his new career choice as a Soccer Coach.

While at Murray State, he also worked as an assistant coach for the women‚Äôs soccer team, helping the team to the second round of the playoffs.

In 2018, Coach Connor moved to East Central University (Ada,OK) Coach Connor is currently still a part of the ECU women‚Äôs soccer program as an Assistant Coach and Recruiter.

Connor also has professional playing history spending time at Pucket FC (Thailand) and Doncaster Rovers U19 (England).

Our final female Senior Tennis player is, Makila Case!

Makila is the daughter of Jodie Eades and Breck Case. Her tennis honors and awards include qualifying for the State Tournament sophomore year, placing 4th at State junior year., and receiving the hardest worker award. Her advice to underclassmen is to try new things because I didn‚Äôt see myself playing tennis until I gave it a try and it turns out that I actually love it. Also, don‚Äôt ever take anything for granted because it can be taken away just like that. Makila's future plans are to attend Murray State in Tishomingo to play Softball and study Early Childhood Development. Her most memorable tennis moment was junior year when Makalia and I placed 4th at 2 Doubles at State. And going to tournaments with my teammates and making memories that we will always remember.

Parents,

Our administrators, teachers and instructional support staff are working hard this week to develop a continuing learning plan that will help your children finish the school year strong. We understand that this ongoing instruction cannot be delivered through a one-size-fits-all approach. As a reminder, academic instruction does not begin again until April 6.

We know that you and your children have many questions about what the remainder of the school will be like. We are working on those plans and details now. We will provide information as it becomes available. When completed, we believe our continuous learning plan will allow us to keep students on track, while also protecting what is most important, their health and well-being.

post_text:
Parents: The Oklahoma State Superintendent Joy Hofmeister will propose to the State Board of Education tomorrow that they approve continuous learning for students starting April 6 & for school buildings to remain closed in every school in the State of Oklahoma. When the decision is made, it will hit all local and state news media outlets and everyone will know.

If the State Board of Education approves her proposal, the district will begin putting a plan together for what the rest of the school year will look like for students and staff. This will take some time and we ask for your cooperation and patience. When the plan is finalized, we will let you know via our School Messenger Service, our website and here on Facebook. Again, thank you for understanding that we cannot answer all your questions via Facebook Messenger.
